      'Central banks raise interest rates to cool inflation. Higher rates make borrowing more expensive, which slows spending and investment. That can reduce demand enough to bring inflation back toward target — usually around 2% in places like the US and EU. The tradeoff is that economic growth can slow and unemployment can rise, which is why central banks move carefully.',
      'Supply has improved in many sectors. Shipping costs have come down, and goods shortages have eased. But labour costs, rent, and some services have stayed sticky — they don’t fall as quickly as commodity prices. So inflation has come down from its peak but is still above what policymakers want in many places.',
      'When will it go down? Forecasts vary. If growth slows and labour markets soften, inflation could drift toward target over the next year or two. If demand stays strong or new shocks hit (energy, food, supply chains), it could stay higher for longer. Central banks say they’ll keep rates high enough for as long as needed; they don’t want to cut too early and let inflation flare again.',
      'For you: lock in better rates on savings where you can, pay down high-interest debt, and expect some prices to stay higher than pre-pandemic. Budgeting and an emergency fund matter more when the cost of living is volatile.',
