      'Climate change is making fire seasons longer and more intense. Warmer temperatures dry out vegetation faster, and drought leaves more fuel ready to burn. Shifts in rain and snow patterns also affect how much fuel is available and when it’s driest. So even with the same number of ignitions, we’re seeing bigger and more destructive fires in many regions.',
      'Land use and forest management matter. Decades of fire suppression in some areas have left dense, continuous fuel. Prescribed burns and thinning can reduce that load so that when a fire does start, it’s easier to control. Building codes and defensible space around homes — clearing brush, using fire-resistant materials — help structures survive when fire comes.',
      'Prevention also means hardening infrastructure: burying or insulating power lines in high-risk areas, and making sure equipment and human activity don’t create sparks when conditions are dangerous. Public messaging and restrictions on outdoor burning during high fire danger can reduce accidental ignitions.',
