      '5G adds new frequency bands, including higher “millimetre wave” bands in some areas. These still sit in the non-ionizing part of the spectrum. They don’t penetrate as far and are absorbed more by skin and surface tissue, but the power levels from base stations and devices are regulated and kept low. Health agencies like the WHO and national bodies have reviewed the evidence and don’t recommend different exposure limits for 5G than for earlier mobile tech.',
      'Some people report symptoms they attribute to electromagnetic exposure — often called “electromagnetic hypersensitivity.” Studies that have tested this under controlled conditions haven’t found a clear link: when people don’t know whether a source is on or off, they can’t consistently tell. That doesn’t mean the symptoms aren’t real; it suggests the cause may be something other than the radiation itself.',
