      'Daylight saving time (DST) is the practice of moving clocks forward by an hour in spring and back in fall so that evening daylight lasts longer in the summer. The idea is to make better use of natural light and, historically, to save energy (though the energy savings in the modern era are disputed).',
      'The concept goes back centuries, but it was widely adopted in the 20th century — during World Wars for extra evening light, and then as a permanent or seasonal policy in many countries. Not everyone uses it: large parts of Africa, Asia, and some of the US (e.g. Arizona, Hawaii) don’t switch.',
      'Supporters say it gives more usable daylight after work and school, which can encourage outdoor activity and reduce some evening energy use. Opponents point to health and safety downsides: the twice-yearly shift is linked to more sleep disruption, heart issues, and even traffic accidents in the days around the change. Many people would prefer to pick one time and stick with it.',
      'Permanent standard time (no “spring forward”) is what sleep and health experts often recommend — it’s closer to the sun’s natural cycle. Permanent daylight saving would give later sunsets year-round but darker mornings in winter. Politically, there’s been talk of making DST permanent in the US and elsewhere, but it’s stalled over whether to lock in standard or daylight time and how it affects different regions.',
      'So we’re likely to keep switching for a while unless lawmakers agree on one option. In the meantime, the best personal fix is to protect your sleep around the clock change: go to bed a bit earlier before “spring forward,” and give yourself a little extra light and wind-down time before “fall back.”',
